SOURCE wiki/concepts/Critical Thinking/Survivorship Bias.md
SURVIVORSHIP BIAS
PRINCIPLE
Survivorship bias occurs when we draw conclusions from winners while ignoring the losers who used the same strategy. The visible survivors distort our understanding of what actually works. 
CLASSIC EXAMPLE
During WWII, Abraham Wald studied bullet holes on returning bombers. The military wanted to armor the areas with the most damage. Wald argued the opposite: armor the areas with no damage, because planes hit there never returned. 
DECISION CRITIC APPLICATION
Use this model during Decomposition (Steps 1-2) and Challenge (Steps 5-6) to surface hidden data gaps. 
VERIFICATION QUESTIONS
When a decision cites evidence of success: 
What failures used the same approach but are not visible? Are we studying survivors or the full population? What data are we missing because failures were discarded? IT sample self-selected (only successes reported)? 
RED FLAGS IN DECISIONS
Signal Risk "Company X did this and succeeded" Ignoring companies that did the same and failed "Our successful projects all used pattern Y" Failed projects using Y were forgotten "This approach always works" Selection bias in evidence "Top performers do Z" Studying survivors, not the full cohort "We've never had a problem with this" Problems were silently discarded or unreported 
CONTRARIAN PERSPECTIVES (STEP 5)
Generate these challenges when survivorship bias is suspected: 
"How many teams tried this approach and failed? Where is that data?" "Are we looking at the planes that came back, or the ones that didn't?" "Is our evidence base self-selected?" 
FAILURE MODES (FOR INVERSION ANALYSIS)
Adopting a strategy because visible successes used it, ignoring invisible failures Reinforcing existing patterns because OTir successes are measured Dismissing alternatives because no visible successes exist (they were never tried) Over-investing in approaches with high visibility but unknown failure rates 
PRACTICAL CHECKLIST
Before accepting evidence-based claims as VERIFIED: 
[ ] Failure cases examined, not just successes [ ] Sample includes non-survivors (full population) [ ] Selection mechanism for evidence is understood [ ] Base rate of success/failure is known or estimated [ ] Alternative explanations for observed pattern considered 
RELATED MODELS
CONFIRMATION_BIAS seeking evidence that supports existing beliefs